流水线中将同时存在5条不同的指令并行执行
The pipeline allows five different instructions to be processed in parallel, one in each of the five functional stages.

数据存储器
Data storage units used to hold data during pipeline processing, synchronized with the clock.

时钟周期
A single cycle of the clock signal (CLK) that triggers data latching and processing transitions in the pipeline.<SEP>A clock cycle is the basic unit of time in a processor, with ideal pipeline operation completing one instruction per clock cycle.

Instruction Decoder
The Instruction Decoder is a circuit that converts the n-bit opcode from the instruction register into 2^n output signals, each corresponding to a unique instruction.<SEP>The Instruction Decoder (ID) interprets the operation code of an instruction and prepares control signals for execution.

Control Unit
The Control Unit (CU) is a component of the CPU responsible for generating control signals that coordinate the operations of the processor based on instruction decoding, clock pulses, and feedback from the execution unit.<SEP>The Control Unit is the component within the CPU that manages instruction execution by generating appropriate control signals.<SEP>The Control Unit is the component of a CPU responsible for generating control signals to manage and coordinate the operations within the Data Path.<SEP>The control unit generates control signals to sequence operations and issue commands such as read and write to memory.

Clock Pulse
The clock pulse is an electrical signal with a frequency equal to the machine’s main frequency, used to synchronize operations within the control unit.

Instruction Opcode
The instruction opcode is the part of an instruction that specifies the operation to be performed and determines the control signals generated by the control unit.

Flag
The flag is a feedback signal from the execution unit indicating the status of the CPU, such as zero, carry, or overflow.

Timing Generator
The Timing Generator, also known as the节拍发生器, produces timing signals (ticks) that regulate the sequence of micro-operations within each clock cycle.

Combinational Logic Controller
The combinational logic controller is an alternative name for the hardwired controller, emphasizing its implementation using combinational logic gates.

Hardwired Controller
The hardwired controller is a type of control unit in a CPU that uses complex combinational logic circuits and flip-flops to generate micro-operation control signals based on instruction requirements, timing, and system state.<SEP>The hardwired controller is a type of control unit that uses combinational logic circuits to generate control signals, known for its high speed due to minimal circuit delay.

Micro-operation Command
A micro-operation command is a control signal that initiates a basic operation within the CPU, issued in a specific time order by the control unit.

Microprogramming Method
The microprogramming method is an alternative approach to implementing control logic that overcomes the complexity and inflexibility of hardwired controllers by using a sequence of microinstructions stored in control memory.

Instruction Register
The Instruction Register (IR) stores the instruction currently being executed and provides the opcode to the instruction decoder.<SEP>The instruction register (IR) holds the instruction fetched from main memory.<SEP>The Instruction Register stores the currently fetched instruction for decoding and execution.<SEP>Instruction Register stores the current instruction being executed by the CPU.<SEP>The Instruction Register (IR) holds the current instruction being executed.<SEP>The instruction register holds the current instruction being executed and receives data from the memory data register.

RISC
RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computing) is a processor design philosophy that typically employs hardwired controllers for high-speed execution.

Maintainability
Maintainability refers to the ease of debugging and updating a controller, which is improved in microprogrammed controllers.

Speed
Speed refers to the performance metric of a controller, where hardwired controllers are faster due to direct logic implementation.

Combinational Logic Circuits
Combinational logic circuits are hardware components used in hardwired controllers that generate control signals based on input conditions.

Microprogrammed Controller
The microprogrammed controller is a control unit that uses a control storage unit to store microinstructions, offering flexibility and ease of modification.

Control Storage Unit
The control storage unit is a memory component in a microprogrammed controller that stores microinstructions for executing machine instructions.

Regularity
Regularity denotes a consistent and standardized design structure, a key advantage of microprogrammed controllers.

Flexibility
Flexibility is a design characteristic that allows modification or addition of new functions, a strength of microprogrammed controllers.

Functionality
Functionality refers to the ability of a controller to support new features or operations, limited in hardwired controllers after design.

Combination Logic Controller
The combination logic controller is an alternative name for the hardwired controller, emphasizing its reliance on combinational logic circuits to generate control signals.

Instruction Execution
Instruction execution is the process by which a control unit processes machine instructions, influenced by the controller type.<SEP>Instruction Execution refers to the process by which the CPU interprets and performs a single instruction.<SEP>Instruction Execution refers to the process by which a CPU carries out the operations specified by a machine instruction, involving data flow through the Data Path.<SEP>Instruction execution refers to the CPU processing of machine instructions, which is distinct from interrupt generation.

Control Signal Generation
Control signal generation is the process of producing timing and operational signals within a controller, determined by its design.<SEP>Control Signal Generation is the process by which the controller produces signals to manage and coordinate the functional units of the CPU.

Control Storage
The control storage is a dedicated memory within the CPU that stores microprograms, implemented using ROM.

Microcycle
A microcycle is the time required to fetch and execute one microinstruction from the control storage, typically equivalent to one clock cycle.

Operation Control Field
The operation control field, also known as the microoperation code field, generates the necessary control signals for a given step in a microprogram.

Microprogram Controller
The microprogram controller uses stored logic to implement machine instructions by converting them into microprograms stored in a control memory, with microoperations generated by microinstructions.

Microinstruction
A microinstruction is a collection of microcommands that defines one step of a microprogram, containing operation control and sequence control fields.

Microoperation
A microoperation is the basic action performed by the execution unit in response to a microcommand, representing the smallest unit in the control sequence.

Sequence Control Field
The sequence control field, also known as the microaddress code field, determines the address of the next microinstruction to be executed.

Microcommand
A microcommand is a control signal sent from the control unit to the execution unit, representing a specific control action, such as enabling a gate or triggering a register.

Microprogram
A microprogram is an ordered sequence of microinstructions that describes the execution of a machine instruction, serving as a real-time interpreter for machine instructions.

Machine Instruction
A machine instruction is a command in a program that the processor executes directly, composed of opcode and operands.

Address Register
The address register (MAR) stores the address for reading from or writing to main memory.

Microinstruction Address Register
The microinstruction address register (μPC or CMAR) holds the address within the control storage for the next microinstruction to be executed.

Program
A program is an ordered set of machine instructions designed to perform a specific function.

Microinstruction Register
The microinstruction register (μIR or CMDR) stores the microinstruction read from control storage.

ROM
ROM is a read-only memory used to implement control storage for storing microprograms.

RAM
RAM is a random-access memory used to implement main memory for storing programs and data.

Microcommand Mutual Exclusivity
Microcommand mutual exclusivity refers to the condition that certain microcommands cannot be executed simultaneously in the system.

Microcommand Compatibility
Microcommand compatibility refers to the property that allows certain microcommands to be executed simultaneously without conflict.

Control Hazard
Control hazard refers to a situation in a processor pipeline where the execution order of instructions is changed due to transfer, return, interrupt, or exception, leading to a disruption in the instruction flow.<SEP>Control hazard occurs due to the uncertainty in branch or jump instructions, disrupting the linear flow of the pipeline.

Branch Instruction
Branch instruction is a type of command that alters the normal sequential execution of instructions by changing the flow of control.

Static Branch Prediction
Static branch prediction is a simple method that uses fixed rules, such as always predicting a branch as not taken.

NOP Instruction
NOP (No Operation) instruction is a placeholder used in software to insert idle cycles to resolve timing issues in processor pipelines.<SEP>A NOP (No Operation) instruction is an artificial instruction inserted into the code to delay execution and resolve timing conflicts.

Delay Loss Time Slot C
Delay loss time slot C represents the number of clock cycles delayed due to pipeline blocking from control hazards.

Program Counter
Program Counter (PC) is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed and is modified during control flow changes.<SEP>The Program Counter (PC) holds the address of the next instruction to be executed and is incremented after each instruction fetch.<SEP>Program Counter holds the address of the next instruction to be executed and automatically increments for sequential execution.<SEP>A program counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed, essential in instruction processing.<SEP>The Program Counter (PC) holds the address of the next instruction to be executed.<SEP>A program counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed and is maintained independently for each thread in hardware multithreading.<SEP>The program counter is a register that holds the address of the next instruction to be executed and can send its content to the memory address register.

Branch Prediction
Branch prediction is a technique used by processors to guess the outcome of a branch instruction and prefetch the next instruction to reduce pipeline stalls.

Pipeline Stall
Pipeline stall occurs when the execution of subsequent instructions is delayed due to a control hazard or other pipeline blocking condition.<SEP>A pipeline stall occurs when the processor cannot execute the next instruction due to a dependency or delay, such as a cache miss, requiring a pause in execution.

Dynamic Branch Prediction
Dynamic branch prediction uses historical data from previous branch executions to make more accurate predictions.<SEP>Dynamic Branch Prediction is a technique used in superscalar CPUs to anticipate the outcome of branch instructions, enabling more efficient out-of-order execution and reducing pipeline stalls.

Cache Miss
Cache miss occurs when requested data is not found in the cache, causing the processor to access slower main memory and potentially stalling the pipeline.<SEP>A cache miss is a condition in which the requested data is not found in the cache, forcing the processor to fetch it from main memory, causing a delay.

Arithmetic Logic Unit
The Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) is a component of the CPU responsible for performing arithmetic and logical operations on data.<SEP>Arithmetic Logic Unit is a digital circuit within the CPU that performs arithmetic and logical operations on data.<SEP>An Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) is a digital circuit that performs arithmetic and logical operations and is a key component in data paths.<SEP>The Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) is a core component of the运算器, responsible for performing arithmetic and logical operations.<SEP>The arithmetic logic unit performs arithmetic and logical operations and requires input data to be held in temporary registers to maintain stability during computation.

Time Control
Time control manages the timing, duration, and sequence of operational signals within the CPU.

Operation Control
Operation control is a CPU function that generates and coordinates signals required to execute instructions across hardware components.

Instruction Control
Instruction control refers to the process of fetching, analyzing, and executing instructions to manage the sequence of program execution.

Controller
The controller is a component of the CPU that coordinates and manages the execution of instructions across computer components.

Interrupt Handling
Interrupt handling deals with the detection and response to abnormal situations or external requests during program execution.

Data Processing
Data processing involves performing arithmetic and logical operations on data to produce results.

Program Execution
Program execution is the process by which a computer carries out a sequence of instructions stored in memory.

Fetch Phase
The fetch phase involves retrieving an instruction from memory and analyzing it, also referred to as the fetch cycle.

Execute Phase
The execute phase is responsible for performing the actual operation specified by the instruction, also known as the execution cycle.

JMPX Instruction
JMPX is an unconditional transfer instruction that does not require accessing main memory during execution, thus only including fetch and execute phases.

Input/Output Device
An input/output device is a peripheral component that communicates with the CPU, typically requiring interrupt handling for data transfer.

Beat
A beat is a subdivision of a machine cycle used in older computer systems to define precise timing for operations.

Machine Cycle
A machine cycle is a historical grouping of operations such as fetch, operand fetch, execution, and interrupt response in early computer systems.

Stack Pointer
The Stack Pointer (SP) keeps track of the top of the stack, which grows toward lower memory addresses.<SEP>Stack Pointer is a register that indicates the top of the stack in memory, used for managing function calls and local variables.

Pulse
A pulse is a basic timing unit within a beat used to synchronize internal CPU operations.

Execution Phase
The execution phase follows the indirect addressing cycle only when indirect addressing is used.

System Bus
System bus connects different components of a computer system, such as the CPU, memory, and I/O interfaces.

CPU Internal Multi Bus Architecture
CPU internal multi bus architecture uses two or more buses, enabling simultaneous data transmission across multiple paths and improving instruction execution efficiency.

CPU Internal Single Bus Architecture
CPU internal single bus architecture connects ALU and all registers to a single internal bus, resulting in simple design but high data transfer conflicts and low performance.

Single Bus Structure Data Path
Single bus structure data path is a basic CPU architecture where all components share a single internal bus, leading to potential data conflicts and limited performance.

Multi Bus Structure Data Path
Multi bus structure data path allows multiple data transfers in parallel by connecting registers to multiple public buses, enhancing performance compared to single bus systems.

Dedicated Data Path
Dedicated data path arranges circuit connections based on data and address flow directions during instruction execution, eliminating shared bus usage and achieving high performance at the cost of increased hardware.

Single Cycle Processor
A single cycle processor (CPI=1) cannot use the single bus method because only one operation can occur per clock cycle, limiting the completion of all instruction steps.<SEP>The single cycle processor executes all instructions within a single clock cycle, requiring each instruction to take the time of the longest instruction, leading to inefficiency for shorter instructions.

Internal Bus
Internal bus refers to the communication pathways within a single component, such as the CPU, connecting its internal registers and arithmetic units.

Registers
Registers are high-speed storage units within the CPU used to temporarily hold data and instructions during processing.

Performance
Performance refers to the efficiency and speed of instruction execution in a data path architecture, influenced by bus structure and data transfer capability.

Instruction Execution Efficiency
Instruction execution efficiency measures how quickly and effectively a processor completes instruction steps, which is improved by multi bus and dedicated data path structures.

Data Transfer Conflict
Data transfer conflict occurs when multiple components attempt to use a shared bus simultaneously, leading to bottlenecks and reduced performance in single bus architectures.

Hardware Complexity
Hardware complexity refers to the physical and circuit design burden of implementing a data path, which increases significantly in dedicated data path systems.

Register
Register is a small, fast storage location within the CPU used to hold data, instructions, or addresses temporarily during processing.<SEP>A register is a sequential logic element that stores binary data and is used for temporary storage in data paths.<SEP>A register is a small, fast storage location within the CPU used to hold data temporarily during processing.

User Visible Register
User visible registers are accessible to programmers and can be directly manipulated in assembly or machine language to reduce memory access.

Program Status Word Register
Program Status Word Register stores status flags from arithmetic and logic operations, such as overflow, sign, zero, and carry.<SEP>The Program Status Word Register (PSW) stores the status flags (e.g., ZF, SF, OF, CF) resulting from arithmetic and logical operations.

General Purpose Register Group
General Purpose Register Group consists of registers that store operands, addresses, and intermediate results, such as AX, BX, CX, DX, SP.<SEP>A general purpose register group consists of multiple registers used for storing data and operands during program execution.<SEP>The General Purpose Register Group (GPRs) consists of multiple registers used for general data storage and manipulation in the CPU.<SEP>A general purpose register group is a set of registers allocated uniquely for each thread in hardware multithreading to store thread-specific data.

Base Index Register
Base Index Register is a type of register used for address calculation in memory access operations.

User Invisible Register
User invisible registers are not accessible to programmers and are used internally by control units to manage CPU operations.

Memory Address Register
Memory Address Register stores the address of a memory location to be accessed.<SEP>The memory address register holds the address of the memory location to be accessed and can receive data from the bus.

Memory Data Register
Memory Data Register holds data being transferred to or from memory.<SEP>The memory data register temporarily holds data transferred between the CPU and main memory.

Temporary Register
Temporary Register is used to temporarily hold data retrieved from the data bus or general-purpose registers before it is sent to the ALU.

Shift Register
Shift Register holds data that can be shifted left or right based on control signals, enabling bit manipulation.<SEP>A shift register is a sequential logic element that shifts data bits through its stages, used for data manipulation.

Accumulator
Accumulator is a register used to store intermediate results of arithmetic and logical operations performed by the ALU.<SEP>The accumulator is a register that holds the result of arithmetic and logical operations and can be updated by writing data from temporary register Z.

Overflow Flag
Overflow Flag is a single bit in the Program Status Word Register that indicates when the result of an arithmetic operation exceeds the maximum representable value.

Sign Flag
Sign Flag is a single bit in the Program Status Word Register that indicates whether the result of an operation is negative.

Zero Flag
Zero Flag is a single bit in the Program Status Word Register that indicates whether the result of an operation is zero.

Machine Language
Machine Language is a low-level programming language consisting of binary codes directly executed by the CPU.

Carry Flag
Carry Flag is a single bit in the Program Status Word Register that indicates a carry out from the most significant bit during addition or a borrow in subtraction.

Assembly Language
Assembly Language is a low-level programming language that uses symbolic representations of machine instructions.

On-Chip Multi-Processor
On-chip multi-processor refers to a multi-core processor where multiple cores are integrated onto a single chip.

Parallel Execution
Parallel execution is the simultaneous execution of multiple threads or processes on separate cores, enabling true concurrency.

Cache
Cache is a high-speed memory used by each core or shared among cores to improve data access speed.

Multi-Core Processor
A multi-core processor integrates multiple processing units, called cores, into a single CPU, enabling parallel execution of tasks.

Multi-Process Execution
Multi-process execution refers to running multiple processes concurrently, often used in conjunction with multi-threading to enhance performance.

Multi-Threaded Execution
Multi-threaded execution is a technique used in multi-core systems where multiple threads run simultaneously to maximize hardware utilization.

Core
A core is an individual processing unit within a multi-core processor, capable of executing instructions independently.

Interleaved Execution
Interleaved execution describes the behavior of multi-threading on a single core, where threads take turns and do not execute simultaneously.

Single-Core System
A single-core system has only one processing unit and cannot support true parallel execution of threads.

Exception Handling Procedure
The exception handling procedure is the process by which the CPU responds to and resolves an exception event.

Exception
An exception is an unexpected event generated internally by the CPU, detected synchronously during the execution of an instruction.<SEP>An exception is an event occurring during CPU instruction execution that requires immediate handling.<SEP>An exception is a hardware-detected event that occurs during the execution of a specific instruction, such as page fault or overflow.

Interrupt Handling Procedure
The interrupt handling procedure is the process by which the CPU responds to and resolves an interrupt request.

User Program
User program is the software being executed by the CPU, which can be interrupted or suspended during execution.

Interrupt Request Signal
Interrupt request signal is a signal sent from an external device to the CPU to initiate an interrupt.

Interrupt
An interrupt is a request from an external device to the CPU, typically for input or output operations, triggered asynchronously.<SEP>An interrupt is a signal requesting the CPU to suspend its current operations and handle a higher-priority task.<SEP>An interrupt is an event from outside the CPU that is unrelated to instruction execution, such as I/O device signals or special events like pressing the Esc key or timer expiration.

Instruction i
Instruction i refers to the i-th instruction in the user program being executed by the CPU.

Operating System
The operating system manages hardware resources and handles exceptions and interrupts through system routines and device drivers.

Exception Return Instruction
Exception return instruction is a CPU instruction used to resume execution after an exception has been handled.

Interrupt Return Instruction
Interrupt return instruction is a CPU instruction used to resume execution after an interrupt has been handled.

Fatal Error
A fatal error is a non-recoverable issue detected during exception or interrupt handling, leading to the termination of the user program.

Instruction i+1
Instruction i+1 refers to the next instruction following the i-th instruction in the user program, which the CPU resumes execution from after handling an interrupt.

Asynchronous Event
An asynchronous event is an occurrence that is independent of the current instruction execution, such as an interrupt triggered by an external device.

Synchronous Event
A synchronous event is an occurrence that happens in lockstep with the instruction execution, such as an exception detected by the CPU during instruction processing.

Device Driver
Device driver is a software component that allows the operating system to communicate with hardware devices.

data.entity_name: Identify Exception and Interrupt and Transfer to Handler
data.content:
Identify Exception and Interrupt and Transfer to Handler
This method identifies the source of the exception or interrupt and transfers control to the appropriate handler.

Exception Response Process
The exception response process is the sequence of steps the CPU follows when handling an exception.

Save Breakpoint and Program State
Saving breakpoint and program state ensures the CPU can resume the interrupted program correctly later.

Disable Interrupts
Disable interrupts is a step in the response process to prevent new interrupts from disrupting the current handling.

Interrupt Response Process
The interrupt response process is the sequence of steps the CPU follows when responding to an interrupt request.

Interrupt Allowance (IF) Trigger
The IF trigger controls whether the CPU can respond to interrupts; if set to 1, interrupts are allowed; if set to 0, interrupts are disabled.

data.entity_name: Unified Exception or Interrupt Query Program
data.content:
Unified Exception or Interrupt Query Program
The unified query program is used by the operating system to detect and prioritize exceptions and interrupts.

Specific Register
A specific register is an alternative storage location to the stack for saving breakpoint and PSW values.

Breakpoint
The breakpoint is the return address where the CPU will resume execution after handling the exception or interrupt.<SEP>A breakpoint is a debugging tool that sets a trap to suspend execution at a specific instruction for inspection.

Software Identification
Software identification involves using a status register and a query program to determine the type of exception or interrupt.

Exception Status Register
The exception status register records the cause of an exception and is used in software-based identification.

Program Status Word (PSW)
The PSW contains the current state of the CPU and must be saved during exception or interrupt handling to restore it later.

Hardware Identification
Hardware identification, also known as vector interrupt, uses a vector table to map interrupt type numbers to handler addresses.

Interrupt Vector Table
The interrupt vector table maps each interrupt type number to its corresponding interrupt vector.

Interrupt Type Number
Each interrupt or exception is assigned a unique number used to identify it in the vector table.

Interrupt Service Program
The interrupt service program is the routine executed by the CPU after identifying an interrupt, responsible for handling the event.

Interrupt Vector
The interrupt vector is the starting address of an interrupt service routine and is stored in the interrupt vector table.

Single Interrupt or Exception Handling
The entire response process is atomic and cannot be interrupted during execution.

μPC
μPC (Microprogram Counter) stores the address of the current microinstruction and is used to control the flow of microinstruction execution.<SEP>μPC (Microprogram Counter) is the register that holds the address of the current microinstruction being executed.

指令寄存器
The instruction register stores the machine instruction fetched from main memory after execution of the fetch microprogram.

微指令地址寄存器
The microinstruction address register receives microaddresses from the microaddress formation component and prepares for microinstruction reading.

微地址形成部件
The microaddress formation component generates initial and subsequent microaddresses to ensure continuous execution of microinstructions.<SEP>The microaddress formation unit generates the starting address of a microprogram based on the machine instruction's operation code.

微指令寄存器
The microinstruction register holds the microinstruction word, with its bit length equal to the microinstruction word length.

CM
CM (Control Memory) refers to the control storage used to hold microprograms for various machine instructions.

控制存储器
The control memory is the core component of the microprogram controller, storing microprograms corresponding to each machine instruction.<SEP>Control memory stores microinstructions and is used to generate control signals during instruction execution.

取指微程序
The fetch microprogram is a standardized microprogram responsible for fetching machine instructions from main memory and loading them into the instruction register.

机器指令
A machine instruction is a low-level command executed directly by a computer's processor, each corresponding to a specific microprogram.

μIR
μIR (Microinstruction Register) is the component that receives and holds the microinstruction read from the control memory during execution.

间址周期微程序
The indirect addressing cycle microprogram handles the specific microcommands required during the indirect addressing phase of instruction execution.

微程序
A microprogram is a sequence of microinstructions that collectively implement a single machine instruction.

中断周期微程序
The interrupt cycle microprogram manages the microcommands needed during the interrupt handling phase of execution.

Structural Hazard
Structural hazard occurs when multiple instructions attempt to use the same hardware resource at the same time, also known as resource conflict.

Memory Access Conflict
Memory access conflict occurs when two instructions attempt to access the same memory unit simultaneously, such as during instruction fetch and data load.

Load Instruction
A load instruction retrieves data from memory and stores it in a register, commonly causing data hazards if followed by an instruction that uses the loaded value.

Read After Write Conflict
Read After Write (RAW) conflict is a type of data hazard where a subsequent instruction attempts to read a register before the preceding instruction has written to it.

Instruction Pipeline
The instruction pipeline is a technique in computer architecture that allows multiple instructions to be processed at different stages simultaneously, but can experience stalls due to various types of hazards.

Data Hazard
Data hazard arises when a later instruction depends on the result of an earlier instruction that has not yet been produced.

Pipeline Hazard
Pipeline hazard refers to a situation in which subsequent instructions cannot execute correctly, causing a stall in the instruction pipeline.

Add Instruction
An add instruction performs addition between two registers and stores the result in a destination register, often subject to data hazards.

Forwarding Path
A forwarding path, or bypass path, is a dedicated circuit in a processor that forwards results directly from one stage to another, avoiding delays due to data hazards.

Instruction Memory
Instruction memory stores the program instructions and is accessed during the instruction fetch stage of the pipeline.

Register Read Port
The register read port is a component used to read values from registers during instruction execution.

Register Write Port
The register write port is a component used to write results back to registers during the write-back stage.

L1 Cache
L1 Cache is the first-level on-chip cache in a processor, often split into separate instruction and data caches to avoid resource conflicts.

Data Memory
Data memory stores data and is used during the memory access stage of the pipeline.

Instruction Fetch Stage
The instruction fetch stage (IF) is the first phase in a pipeline, where the next instruction is fetched from memory.

Memory Stage
The memory stage (MEM) is the phase in a pipeline where data is accessed from memory or stored back to memory.

Load-Use Data Hazard
A load-use data hazard occurs when a load instruction is immediately followed by an instruction that uses the loaded value, and the data is not yet available.

Register File
The register file is a small, fast storage unit that holds processor registers and provides read/write ports.

Write-Back Stage
The write-back stage (WB) is the final phase in a pipelined processor where the result of an instruction is written back to a register.<SEP>Write-Back Stage is the fifth stage in the instruction pipeline, responsible for writing the result back to a register.

Compiler Optimization
Compiler optimization is a technique used to rearrange instructions during compilation to avoid hazards like load-use conflicts.

Execute Stage
The execute stage (EX) is the phase where arithmetic and logical operations are performed.<SEP>Execute Stage is the third stage in the instruction pipeline, responsible for performing arithmetic or logical operations.

Non-OutOfOrder Execution
Non-out-of-order execution refers to a pipelining model where instructions are executed strictly in program order, preventing speculation and limiting data hazard types to only Read After Write (RAW) conflicts.

Resource Conflict
Structural hazards are also referred to as resource conflicts caused by limited hardware components being accessed by multiple instructions at once.

Execution Stage
The execute stage produces results that may be forwarded to the write-back stage for register update.

Single Step Tracking
Single step tracking is a debugging technique where the CPU executes one instruction at a time, often using a trap mechanism.

Overflow
Overflow is a programmatic exception that occurs when a calculation exceeds the maximum value representable in a given data format.

Programmable Exception
Programmable exception, also known as software interrupt, is an exception triggered by the execution of specific instructions within the CPU.

Hard Fault Interrupt
Hard fault interrupt is an exception caused by hardware-level issues such as memory parity errors or bus errors.

Illegal Instruction
An illegal instruction is a programmatic exception that occurs when the CPU attempts to execute an unrecognized or invalid instruction.

Division By Zero
Division by zero is a type of programmatic exception that occurs when an integer division operation has a divisor of zero.

Stack Overflow
Stack overflow is a programmatic exception caused by excessive use of the call stack.

Abort
An abort is a type of exception caused by serious hardware faults that prevent program execution and require system restart.

Fault
A fault is a type of exception detected before an instruction completes, allowing potential recovery by restarting the instruction.

Address Out Of Bounds
Address out of bounds is a programmatic exception that occurs when memory access exceeds valid address limits.

Trap
A trap is a prearranged exception triggered by a specific instruction, used for system calls or debugging.

Page Fault
A page fault is a programmatic exception indicating that required memory pages are not currently in main memory.

Segment Fault
A segment fault is a programmatic exception caused by an invalid memory segment access.

System Call
A system call is a mechanism enabling user programs to request services from the operating system kernel.

x86 Machine
The x86 machine is a processor architecture that implements debugging features such as breakpoints and single-step tracking via trap mechanism.

Bus Error
A bus error is a hardware fault caused by abnormal communication on the computer's data bus.

MIPS Architecture
The MIPS architecture is a processor architecture that includes conditional trap instructions such as teq, teqi, tne, and tnei.

Controller Error
A controller error is a hardware fault in a system controller that prevents normal operation.

Page
A page is a fixed-size block of memory used in virtual memory management.

Memory Parity Error
Memory parity error is a hardware-level fault indicating data corruption in memory.

Segment
A segment is a block of memory with defined boundaries, used in segmented memory systems.

Exception Service Routine
An exception service routine is a piece of code executed in response to an exception to handle or recover from it.

Operating System Kernel
The operating system kernel is the core component of an operating system responsible for managing system resources and hardware interactions.

Disk
Disk refers to secondary storage, such as hard drives or SSDs, used to store data persistently.

Superpipeline Technology
Superpipeline Technology increases the number of pipeline stages to allow more instructions to overlap in execution, enhancing instruction throughput by reducing the clock cycle duration.

Dynamic Pipeline Scheduling
Dynamic Pipeline Scheduling enables out-of-order execution by applying techniques such as dynamic branch prediction to optimize instruction scheduling and improve parallelism.

Multiple Issuance Technology
Multiple Issuance Technology enables simultaneous processing of multiple instructions by utilizing multiple internal functional units, allowing multiple instructions to be issued into the pipeline in a single clock cycle.

Out-of-Order Execution
Out-of-Order Execution is a technique where instructions are executed not strictly in program order, but based on data availability and execution readiness, enhancing processing efficiency and throughput.

Very Long Instruction Word Technology
Very Long Instruction Word Technology, also known as static multiple issuance, uses a compiler to identify parallel instruction opportunities and combines them into a single, extended instruction word containing multiple operation fields, requiring multiple processing units.

Superscalar Pipeline Technology
Superscalar Pipeline Technology, also known as dynamic multiple issuance, executes two or more independent instructions per clock cycle through parallel operation, requiring multiple functional units and often employing dynamic scheduling and out-of-order execution.

Advanced Pipeline Technology
Advanced Pipeline Technology refers to techniques for increasing instruction-level parallelism in processors, including superscalar, very long instruction word, and superpipeline methods.

Instruction Throughput
Instruction throughput refers to the number of instructions executed per unit of time, a key metric for measuring processor performance.

Instruction-Level Parallelism
Instruction-Level Parallelism refers to the ability of a processor to execute multiple instructions simultaneously, improving overall performance.<SEP>Instruction-level parallelism refers to the ability of a processor to execute multiple instructions simultaneously within a single thread.

Compiler
A Compiler is a software tool that translates high-level programming code into machine code, enabling the extraction of parallelism in Very Long Instruction Word technology.

Pipeline Register Overhead
Pipeline Register Overhead refers to the resource cost associated with maintaining registers between pipeline stages, which increases with the number of pipeline stages.

Functional Unit
A Functional Unit is a hardware component within a processor responsible for performing specific operations such as arithmetic or logic calculations.<SEP>A functional unit is a hardware component within a processor that performs specific operations, such as arithmetic or logic calculations.

CPI
CPI (Cycles Per Instruction) measures the average number of clock cycles required to execute one instruction, with lower values indicating higher efficiency.<SEP>CPI (Cycles Per Instruction) measures the average number of clock cycles required to execute an instruction, with CPI=1 indicating optimal performance per instruction.

Figure 5.19
Figure 5.19 is a diagram illustrating the configuration of multiple functional units in a simple superscalar CPU.

Simple Superscalar CPU
A Simple Superscalar CPU is a type of processor where instructions are issued and executed in program order, serving as a baseline model before advanced scheduling techniques are applied.

data.entity_name: 微指令的操作控制字段
data.content:
微指令的操作控制字段
The operation control field of a microinstruction is the part responsible for specifying control signals and microcommands.

字段直接编码方式
Field direct encoding method divides the control field into smaller fields, grouping mutually exclusive microcommands in the same field and compatible ones in different fields, with independent encoding for each field.

微指令的编码方式
Microinstruction encoding method refers to the technique used to encode control fields in microinstructions to generate control signals.

直接编码方式
Direct encoding method involves setting each bit in the control field to directly represent a microcommand without requiring decoding.

字段间接编码方式
Field indirect encoding method allows some microcommands in one field to be interpreted by microcommands in another field, resulting in implicit or hidden decoding.

微命令
A microcommand is a signal that controls a specific microoperation in the data path.

微操作
A microoperation is a fundamental operation executed in the data path of a processor.

译码电路
Decoding circuitry converts encoded field signals into actual microcommands.

相容性微命令
Compatible microcommands are those that can be executed simultaneously and are placed in different fields in field direct encoding.

小段
A small segment refers to a subdivided portion of the operation control field in field direct encoding.

互斥性微命令
Mutually exclusive microcommands are those that cannot be executed simultaneously and are grouped within the same field in field direct encoding.

控制存储器容量
Control memory capacity refers to the storage size required for storing microinstructions, which is significantly increased in direct encoding due to long microinstruction word lengths.

3位字段
A 3-bit field can represent up to 7 distinct microcommands, with 000 reserved for indicating no operation.

微指令字长
Microinstruction word length is the number of bits used to represent a microinstruction.

操作并行性
Operation parallelism refers to the ability of multiple microoperations to execute simultaneously.

Multiplexer
A multiplexer is a combinational logic circuit that selects one of several input signals and forwards it to a single output line, commonly used in data paths.

Sequential Logic Element
A sequential logic element is a circuit whose output depends on current inputs and previous states, requiring memory units and clock signals for operation.

Adder
An adder is a digital circuit used to perform addition of binary numbers and is a common combinational logic element in data paths.

Three-State Gate
A three-state gate is a combinational logic element that can output high, low, or high-impedance states, aiding in bus control within data paths.

Data Path
A data path is a component in computing systems that facilitates the movement and processing of data, consisting of combination and sequential logic elements.<SEP>Data Path is the collection of functional units and connections through which data flows in a processor.<SEP>The Data Path is the functional unit within the CPU responsible for data flow and manipulation, including the ALU and registers.<SEP>The Data Path is the component of a CPU that handles the flow of data during instruction execution, encompassing the routes and functional units data passes through.

Decoder
A decoder is a combinational logic circuit that converts binary information into a set of output signals, used in data paths for control and selection.

Combinational Logic Element
A combinational logic element is a type of circuit whose output depends solely on current inputs, with no memory or clock control, and features unidirectional signal flow.

Status Register
A status register stores the current state of a processor, including flags like zero, carry, and overflow.<SEP>The Status Register is a component of the Data Path that stores flags or status indicators resulting from arithmetic and logical operations.

Latch
A latch is a type of sequential logic element that stores data based on input signals and is level-sensitive rather than edge-triggered.

Clock Signal
A clock signal is a periodic signal used to synchronize operations in sequential logic circuits, ensuring timing control.

Output Feedback
Output feedback refers to the condition where output signals influence input behavior, which is absent in combinational logic elements.

No Feedback
Combinational logic elements do not have feedback paths, ensuring output depends only on immediate inputs.

Instruction Pipeline Stages
Instruction Pipeline Stages are the sequential steps an instruction passes through in a processor, including fetch, decode, execute, memory access, and write-back.

Clock Frequency
Clock Frequency is the rate at which a processor executes clock cycles, inversely proportional to the clock cycle duration.

5-Stage Pipeline
Five-Stage Pipeline is a common instruction pipeline model consisting of fetch, decode, execute, memory access, and write-back stages.

Single Cycle Implementation
Single Cycle Implementation is a CPU design approach where each instruction completes in one clock cycle, with the clock period determined by the slowest stage in the data path.

Instruction Execution Time
Instruction Execution Time is the total time taken to complete a single instruction in a processor.

Pipeline Design Principle
Pipeline Design Principle refers to the guidelines for structuring instruction pipelines, including segment count and stage duration based on the most complex instruction.

Fetch Stage
Fetch Stage is the first stage in the instruction pipeline, responsible for retrieving the instruction from memory.

Memory Access Stage
Memory Access Stage is the fourth stage in the instruction pipeline, responsible for reading from or writing to memory.

Decode Stage
Decode Stage is the second stage in the instruction pipeline, responsible for interpreting the instruction and preparing operands.

200ps
200ps is the time duration of the longest individual stage in the pipeline, used to set the clock cycle for the processor.

100ps
100ps is the time duration of the decode and write-back stages.

150ps
150ps is the time duration of the execute stage.

750ps
750ps is the total execution time of an instruction in a single-cycle processor.

1ns
1ns is the execution time per instruction in a pipeline processor, calculated as 5 stages × 200ps.

Pipeline Processor Time
Pipeline Processor Time is computed as (N + 4) × 200ps, reflecting the latency overhead of pipeline initiation.

Single Cycle Processor Time
Single Cycle Processor Time is computed as N × 750ps, representing total time to execute N instructions in single-cycle mode.

Performance Efficiency
Performance Efficiency refers to the improvement in processing throughput achieved by using pipelining over sequential execution for multiple instructions.

N
N represents the number of instructions in a given program.

Stage Length
The length of each pipeline stage must be set to match the longest individual operation to maintain synchronization.

Accumulator Register
The Accumulator Register (ACC) is a special-purpose register used for storing intermediate results during arithmetic and logic operations.

Counter
The Counter (CT) is a register used for counting operations, such as instruction execution cycles or memory addresses.

Shifter Register
The Shifter Register performs bit shifting operations, such as left or right shifts, used in data manipulation.

Timing Circuit
The Timing Circuit generates clock signals used to synchronize operations within the CPU.

Microoperation Signal Generator
The Microoperation Signal Generator produces control signals to execute microcommands during instruction execution.

Computational Core
The Computational Core is the central functional unit of the CPU that performs arithmetic, logical, and conditional operations.

Operation Code
The Operation Code is the portion of an instruction that specifies the type of operation to be performed by the CPU.

Control Signal
A Control Signal is an electrical signal generated by the controller to manage the operation of various CPU components.

Microcommand Sequence
A Microcommand Sequence is a series of low-level control signals used to execute a single instruction.

Hardware Synchronization
Hardware Synchronization refers to the coordination of various CPU components through timing signals to ensure correct execution order.

Conditional Test
The Conditional Test is a function performed by the运算器to evaluate conditions and set status flags such as ZF, SF, OF, and CF for decision-making.

运算器
The运算器performs Conditional Test operations to set status flags (ZF, SF, OF, CF) based on arithmetic and logical results.

General Purpose Registers
General purpose registers are storage units within the Data Path used to hold data temporarily during instruction execution.

Exception and Interrupt Handling Logic
The exception and interrupt handling logic is part of the Data Path responsible for managing exceptional events and interrupts during instruction execution.

Control Signals
Control Signals are generated by the Control Unit to regulate the behavior and operation of the Data Path components.

指令流水线
The instruction pipeline is a technique that improves processor parallelism by breaking the execution of instructions into multiple stages that are executed in a pipelined fashion.

空间上的并行技术
Space-based parallelism involves placing multiple identical functional units in a processor to execute the same task in parallel, often seen in superscalar processors.

超标量处理机
A superscalar processor is a type of processor that can execute multiple instructions per clock cycle by using several functional units working in parallel.

时间上的并行技术
Time-based parallelism splits a task into sub-stages executed in parallel on different functional units, allowing multiple tasks to be processed simultaneously.

取指
The fetch stage retrieves the instruction from the instruction memory or cache.

执行/计算地址
The execute/calculate address stage performs arithmetic or logical operations or calculates memory addresses.

译码/读寄存器
The decode/Read Register stage decodes the instruction and reads operand values from the register file.

访存
The memory access stage performs read or write operations on the memory.

写回
The write back stage writes the result of the instruction execution back to the register file.

指令长度
Instruction length refers to the uniformity of instruction size, which affects the complexity of fetch and decode operations.

指令格式
Instruction format defines the structure of instructions, with consistent layout being beneficial for pipeline efficiency.

指令集
The instruction set is a collection of commands that a processor can understand and execute, which influences pipeline efficiency.

LOAD/STORE型指令
LOAD/STORE instructions are a type of instruction that can access memory only through specific load and store operations, enabling efficient pipeline scheduling.

源寄存器
Source registers are locations in the register file that hold operand data for operations, with consistent placement being preferred.

data.entity_name: 数据和指令在存储器中按边界对齐
data.content:
数据和指令在存储器中按边界对齐
Data and instructions stored in memory are aligned to boundaries, reducing memory access times and improving pipeline performance.

流水段
A pipeline stage is a phase in the instruction execution process, corresponding to a functional unit or step.

data.entity_name: 每条指令的时钟周期数
data.content:
每条指令的时钟周期数
CPI (Cycles Per Instruction) is a metric for processor efficiency, with an ideal value of 1 in a fully pipelined system.

功能部件
Functional units are hardware components responsible for executing specific operations in the processor.

标志
Flags in the control unit are used to determine the branch target address of the next microinstruction.

data.entity_name: 微指令的地址形成方式
data.content:
微指令的地址形成方式
Microinstruction address formation refers to the methods used to determine the address of the next microinstruction in a microprogrammed control unit.

断定方式
The determined method is a technique where the next microinstruction address is directly indicated by the successor address field in the microinstruction.

data.entity_name: 微指令的后继地址字段
data.content:
微指令的后继地址字段
The successor address field in a microinstruction directly specifies the address of the next microinstruction, also known as the determined method.

机器指令的操作码
The operation code of a machine instruction determines the starting address of the microprogram for that instruction.

增量计数器法
The increment counter method uses the formula (μPC)+1→μPC to generate the next microinstruction address when addresses are sequential.

后继微地址
The successor microinstruction address is the address of the next microinstruction to be executed in the microprogram.

垂直型微指令
Vertical microinstructions use an operation code-like field to specify a single microcommand per instruction.

字段直接编码
Field direct encoding divides the control field into subfields, each directly signaling a group of control signals.

data.entity_name: 硬件直接产生微程序入口地址
data.content:
硬件直接产生微程序入口地址
Hardware directly generates the entry address of the microprogram upon power-up, which is used as the fetch cycle microinstruction address.

水平型微指令
Horizontal microinstructions use direct encoding where each bit in the instruction corresponds to one control signal.

字段间接编码
Field indirect encoding uses a subfield to select from a set of control signal patterns, allowing compact representation.

直接编码
Direct encoding assigns one bit in the microinstruction to control each individual control signal.

微指令的格式
The format of a microinstruction refers to the layout and structure of its fields in a microprogrammed control unit.

电源加电后
The event of power-up initializes the microprogram control unit and sets the first microinstruction address.

取指周期微程序
The fetch cycle microprogram is the sequence of microinstructions executed during the instruction fetch phase.

Interrupt Request Signal Line
The interrupt request signal line is a hardware connection through which external I/O devices send interrupt requests to the CPU.

Special Event
A special event refers to user actions (e.g., pressing Esc) or timer expirations that generate interrupt signals.

I/O Interrupt
An I/O interrupt is triggered by input/output devices, such as keyboard input or printer paper shortage, and is signaled via a dedicated interrupt request line.

Maskable Interrupt
A maskable interrupt is a type of interrupt signaled through the INTR line, which can be disabled or enabled by setting a mask in the interrupt controller.

Interrupt Response Cycle
The interrupt response cycle is the process the CPU enters upon detecting an interrupt request, during which it prepares to handle the interrupt.

Maskable Interrupt Request Line INTR
The INTR line is a specific hardware line used to send maskable interrupts to the CPU.

Non-Maskable Interrupt Request Line NMI
The NMI line is a dedicated hardware line for sending non-maskable interrupts, ensuring immediate CPU response.

Non-Maskable Interrupt
A non-maskable interrupt is a high-priority interrupt sent via the NMI line and cannot be disabled; used for critical hardware failures like power loss.

Hardware Fault
A hardware fault, such as power failure, triggers a non-maskable interrupt to ensure rapid system response.

Vector Interrupt
A vector interrupt is a type of interrupt where the service routine address is determined by a vector number, enabling rapid identification of the handler.

Single Interrupt
A single interrupt refers to a system where interrupt handling cannot be interrupted by another interrupt.

Non-Vector Interrupt
A non-vector interrupt requires software or polling methods to identify the interrupt source and service routine address.

Interrupt Controller
The interrupt controller is a hardware component that manages interrupt requests and allows CPU to set masks for maskable interrupts.

Multiple Interrupt
A multiple interrupt allows the CPU to respond to a new interrupt while handling an ongoing one, enabling higher responsiveness.

Hardware Detection
Hardware detection is the mechanism by which all interrupt and exception events are identified and signaled by hardware.

INTR
The maskable interrupt is transmitted via the INTR signal line and can be controlled by the interrupt controller.

NMI
The non-maskable interrupt is transmitted via the NMI signal line and cannot be disabled.

Thread Switching
Thread switching refers to the process of changing execution from one thread to another, which incurs overhead in traditional CPUs.

Fine-Grained Multithreading
Fine-grained multithreading allows threads to alternate instruction execution on a per-clock-cycle basis, enabling interleaved execution without dependence on instruction dependency or pipeline state.

Intel Hyper-Threading
Intel Hyper-Threading is a form of SMT that implements two logical threads per physical core, sharing cache and functional units.

Coarse-Grained Multithreading
Coarse-grained multithreading executes a thread’s instructions for multiple clock cycles before switching, only switching when a significant stall, such as a cache miss, occurs.

Simultaneous Multithreading
Simultaneous multithreading (SMT) enables the execution of multiple instructions from different threads within a single clock cycle, achieving both instruction-level and thread-level parallelism.

Hardware Multithreading
Hardware multithreading is a technique that reduces thread switching overhead by providing dedicated resources for each thread in a CPU.

High-Speed Cache
High-speed cache is a fast memory component shared among threads in a multithreaded processor to reduce memory latency.

Pipeline Processor
The pipeline processor enables parallel execution of instructions by having multiple instructions in different stages simultaneously, aiming to complete one instruction per clock cycle in ideal conditions.

Instruction Execution Cycle
The instruction execution cycle refers to the sequence of steps a processor follows to execute a single instruction, typically involving multiple stages.

Instruction Serial Execution
Instruction serial execution refers to the execution of instructions one after another, without overlap, characteristic of single and multi cycle processors.

Multi Cycle Processor
The multi cycle processor assigns different numbers of clock cycles to different instructions based on their complexity, allowing for more efficient execution but maintaining serial execution.

Instruction Parallel Execution
Instruction parallel execution allows multiple instructions to be processed simultaneously in different stages, a key feature of pipeline processors.

Execution Step
An execution step is a specific phase in the instruction execution cycle, such as fetch, decode, execute, memory access, and write back.

General Purpose Register
General purpose registers are storage elements that hold data and can transfer information to or from the bus via control signals.

Single Bus Data Path
The single bus data path is a system architecture where a single shared bus is used for data transmission between components, with only one component able to use the bus at any given time.

Bus
The bus is a shared set of transmission signal lines that do not store information and allow only one device to transmit at a time.

Temporary Register Y
Temporary register Y stores one operand in a computation sequence and keeps its value active at the ALU’s left input.

Arithmetic Operation
The arithmetic operation involves transferring one operand to temporary register Y, the second to ALU input, computing the result in ALU, and storing it in temporary register Z.

Read Operation
The read operation involves sending a memory address via the program counter to the memory address register, then issuing a read command to transfer data to the memory data register.

Instruction Fetch
The instruction fetch method involves transferring the program counter value to the memory address register, reading the instruction from memory into the memory data register, and loading the instruction into the instruction register.

Write Operation
The write operation involves sending the desired data to the memory data register and the target address to the memory address register, then issuing a write command.

Temporary Register Z
Temporary register Z holds the result output from the ALU before it is written to the destination register.

Program Counter Update
The program counter update method increments the program counter value to prepare for the next instruction after fetching the current instruction.

Transfer Operation
The transfer operation allows updating the program counter with a new address from the instruction register, enabling branching or jump instructions.

Control Signal MARin
Control signal MARin enables the memory address register to accept data from the bus.

Control Signal Rout
Control signal Rout enables the transfer of data from a register to the bus.

Control Signal MDRout
Control signal MDRout enables the memory data register to output its value to the bus.

Control Signal MDRin
Control signal MDRin enables the memory data register to accept data from the bus.

Control Signal IRin
Control signal IRin enables the instruction register to accept data from the bus.

Control Signal PCout
Control signal PCout enables the program counter to output its value to the bus.

Control Signal Rin
Control signal Rin enables the transfer of data from the bus into a register.

Control Signal ACCin
Control signal ACCin enables the accumulator to accept data from the bus.

Control Signal Zout
Control signal Zout enables the temporary register Z to output its value to the bus.

Control Signal Yin
Control signal Yin enables the temporary register Y to accept data from the bus.

Address Field
The address field is a component of the instruction register that contains the target address for a jump or transfer instruction.

Control Signal ALUin
Control signal ALUin enables the arithmetic logic unit to receive data from the bus.

Memory Cycle
A memory cycle is the time required to perform a read or write operation with main memory.

Control Signal PCin
Control signal PCin enables the program counter to accept a new address from the bus during a transfer operation.

Unified Memory Access
Unified Memory Access (UMA) is a type of shared memory multiprocessor where all processors have approximately equal access time to any memory unit, regardless of the requesting processor or accessed memory word.

Shared Memory Multiprocessor
Shared Memory Multiprocessor (SMP) is a multi-processor system with a single physical address space where processors communicate through shared variables and can access any memory location using load/store instructions.

QPI Bus
The QPI (QuickPath Interconnect) bus is a high-speed point-to-point interconnect used by CPUs to communicate with each other and access remote memory in NUMA systems.

Non-Uniform Memory Access
Non-Uniform Memory Access (NUMA) is a type of shared memory multiprocessor where memory access time depends on the processor requesting access and the memory location, due to memory being partitioned among processors.

Memory Controller
The memory controller manages data flow between the processor and system memory; it was initially located in the northbridge chip and later integrated into the CPU.

Northbridge Chip
The northbridge chip is a component that integrated the memory controller and connected the CPU to main memory via the front-side bus.

Local Memory
Local memory refers to the portion of memory directly connected to a CPU, which provides faster access compared to remote memory in NUMA systems.

Front-Side Bus
The front-side bus is a communication interface connecting the CPU to the northbridge chip, creating a bottleneck under high CPU demand.

Remote Memory
Remote memory is the portion of system memory connected to a different CPU, accessed via QPI bus and subject to higher latency in NUMA architectures.

Processor Synchronization
Processor synchronization is the process of coordinating access to shared resources to prevent inconsistent or incorrect execution in multi-processor systems.

Lock Mechanism
A lock mechanism is a synchronization method used to ensure exclusive access to a shared variable, allowing only one processor to modify it at a time.

Shared Variable
A shared variable is a memory location accessed by multiple processors in a shared memory system, requiring synchronization to prevent race conditions.

Race Condition
A race condition occurs when multiple processors access a shared variable simultaneously without proper synchronization, leading to unpredictable results.
